Maybe he felt he didn&#x27;t need to apologize because he was forced to rush and release in iOS6?<p>What if the following conversation happened internally:<p>Scott: &quot;Maps is not ready&quot;
Cook: &quot;Maps must ship as part of iOS6, it&#x27;s the headline feature. We are committed to this time table.&quot;
Scott: &quot;But there are lots of issues, lots of bugs.&quot;
Cook: &quot;Fix as many as possible before release, but we are shipping.&quot;<p>Then, after the fiasco, he is asked to apologize, wouldn&#x27;t you feel that the people who didn&#x27;t take your advice should be the ones to apologize?
